title: Sheath for Brusletto Hunter Knives
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I designed this sheath for my home-built knife.
The blade's dimensions:
L: 132 mm
W. 2 mm
H: 25 mm
The sheath can be constructed in an hour or less, provided the right materials and tools.
A magnet is mounted in the sheath to keep the knife in place.

Printer:

Da Vinci pro 3in1

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0,1 mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Tends to warp

Materials:

1) Misc leather, A5 size
2) Rivets
3) Some good glue
4) Sandpaper, 120 grit and finer
5) Lacquer, color of choice
6) A strong, thin magnet (HDD magnets are perfect)
7) A hole-punch or awl

Step 1

Trace the outline of "Knivskede Skal" onto the leather sheet twice.

Step 2

Cut out the leather pieces using preferred cutting implement.
Leave 2 mm around the edge of the leather piece. this allows room for error and will be sanded away after the build.

Step 3

1)
Glue "Knivskede Skal" and a piece of leather together.

2)
Glue "Knivskede Midterlag" on top of this.

3)
Glue the HDD Magnet on the leather in between the arms of "Knivskede Midterlag"

4) Let the glue cure, if using CA glue, apply catalyst now.

5)
ensure that the force of the magnet is adequate for holding the knife in place when upside down.

Step 4, belt loop

1)
cut out another piece of leather.
Dimensions:
W: 2-3 Cm.
L: 3,5 times the width of your belt

2)
fold this piece of leather onto itself and use the hole-punch/awl to make holes the size of your rivets.
do the same to the second piece of leather.
The holes should be in the same position of both pieces.

3)
rivet the loop to the second piece of leather. the rivets can be reinforced with some glue.

Step 5

Glue the second leather piece onto "Knivskede Midterlag"

Step 6

Use a sharp knife to carve off excess leather around the edges of the sheath and finish with coarse sand-paper.
Sand all surfaces of the sheath

Step 7

Apply a generous amount of lacquer onto the top, sides and bottom of the sheath.

Step 8

Polish the surfaces where lacquer was applied.

Finished Product:
The parts are designed in Autodesk F360

description.text:
A glass bed holder for the QIDI Tech-1. I made this since the standard size glass is not exactly the same size as the bed and corner clamps are problematic and loosen.

The adjustable part goes on the left so the spring holder is toward the front but I guess it could go either way.

You can use the M3 Thumb Nut if you want. It is a remix of one on here but I can't find the maker to give credit!

Feel free to send suggestions for improvements.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2, 5 perimter, 4 bottom, 5 top

Infill:

50%

Notes:

If printed in ABS you may want to scale to 101% to account for shrink. Experiment to get the holes to line up with the bolts on the bed before printing the whole part.
I printed mine in PETG to see how it goes. It fit well and no shrink.
ABS - 230 and pretty standard settings.
PETG - 240 and pretty standard settings.

You only need support under the spring arm at the edge.

Print with perimeter, top, bottom and infill as you see fit.

Hardware

You will probably need longer bolts to replace the ones that go at each corner. There are four and four extra nuts to use in the wing nut parts. Be careful to get the same head type on the bolt so it doesn't stick up above the bed and interfere with you build surface.
When I replaced the standard bolts at each corner with the longer ones I then used the existing nuts to fasten back in place so the heater board is secure.
Desisgned in Fusion 360

comments.text:
Hi, you will probably need longer bolts/screws for the ones (4) at each corner and four more nuts. What I did is added the longer screw and then used the original nuts to secure back in place. Then I added the new nuts to the wing nut parts. I felt this would still leave the heater securely clamped to the bed.
Thanks for asking I will make sure to add this to the part description. I could measure the ones I used this evening and post it.

remixed_from.title: Extended control dial for MonoPrice Select Mini/Malyan M200

title: Perfect Dial for MP Select Mini

description.text: So there are a lot of replacement controller knobs out there for the MP Select Mini and I tried many of them but none of them were what I wanted personally. Sure they worked fine, but I wanted something that kept the original knob top and could still be used with the bed over top of it and one that made spinning the knob easier like for moving the axis or activating the extruder and I wanted something taller as well as I found it just makes using the knob easier.

Printer:

monoprice mp select mini

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1 to .15

Infill:

10-20%

Notes:

I upgraded to Nema 17 motor with .05 leadscrew so your resolution will be different with stock Mini. I would go with decent resolution but you don't have to go fine, it's up to you really.

For infill I did 20% and I used clear PLA filament so the LED light can shine through.

You can probably do it with no supports as the cones are small.

For raft I use Brim to make sure it stays

Slight finishing might be needed

There's not much to post printing.
I should note the cones have sharp points on them, needle like really, but they will wear down naturally with use. If you find them to sharp just hit them with 150 grit or higher sandpaper a few swipes, just a couple/few swipes are needed really to take the sharp points off.

Bottom hole will be cleaned out most likely.

This took a lot of work to get right...

It took me a long time to get this correct and working the way I wanted it to. I opened up Meshmixer and got to work and it took a lot of trial and error with different designs.

Most knobs were sort of flat on the sides but needed something on the sides so you can use your finger with the bed over top of it so I tried many different things like cylinders, squares, triangles and lots of different shapes protruding from it and ended up with cones. This design here was the first one that sort of worked but it still wasn’t quite right.

I ended up with something that resembles a medieval torture device maybe for the final design and it worked perfectly. This design with the cones allows you to put your finger on the side of the dial between the cones and spin it very quickly and easily. You put your finger vertically down between them and spin the dial. One row of cones didn’t work as well as I wanted to I went with two rows and it’s just perfect. The angle of the cones on each side just works perfectly for the tip of your finger or the side of your finger to go between them to easily spin the dial and have control as well. I tried other shapes and designs but they just didn’t work the same.

The original plastic ‘chrome’ cap fits on the dial just fine, I wanted to keep the original cap, I just wanted to keep as much of the original printer as I could, and I liked the looks of the cap.

I played with the height of the knob and got it as high as I could without hitting the bed. The cones on the sides allow you to easily turn the knob with the bed over top of the knob, you can put your finger between then and move it and still push down on the cap.

I printed the final design in clear PLA filament with about 20% infill, it’s sturdy but yet allows the light to shine through.

I’m very happy with how it turned out, it works perfectly, it does exactly what I wanted and works how I want it to. I’ve been using it for a while now and for me it’s the perfect knob for this printer. This knob has and does everything I want it to do and what it needs to do.

I should note I'm not sure if this will work with the Mini V2 as I don't have one but I think the knob is the same, maybe someone can comment and let me know.

Obviously this is considerably simplified from the incredibly ornate sunstone you're used to, but it's got enough of that detail to suggest the sunstone while still being printable on a consumer 3D printer.  
Probably best printed in either a dark green (suggestive of jade) or a metallic color.  You probably want to use a horizontal resolution of 0.1 because layers are only about 0.2mm high.  Note that even at that resolution, and even with this as simple as it is, you'll need a really good printer to get all the detail -- you can see my printer didn't do so good in PLA, there's definite artifacting at this scale.  
There are two versions, one with and one without a loop at the top for making it into jewelry.
If you print one, please post an I Made One photo.

author: LiquidSoap

description.text:
I wanted a way to mount my Drive Pro plow controller. I also had problems with the plow lights accidentally being turned on or off when moving the controller around. This is what I came up with and it worked great for me last winter. I have also created a mount that slides over the emergency brake which is included in the blend file but I did not include g files for that since it is not complete. I have an extender that lifts the controller up off the e-brake, but I am still working on dimensions. The extender I made was not quite high enough. Sorry, but the plow controller wrapper requires drilling for screws to mount the two pieces together, but can easily be drilled to accept 4 or 6 small screws. That is what I did using a drill press, but hand drill should work.
The cover is not subdivided or rounded, it is basically squared off. Since the light switch is now recessed, I have yet to accidentally turn them off yet after a season of plowing.

Printer Brand:

PowerSpec

Printer:

Ultra 3D

Supports:

No

Notes:

I have included the dimensions in the images uploaded. They are also in the blend file.
I used standard print settings in low quality.

Simple Design

As mentioned earlier, I did not use subdivision or rounding of edges. It may be also possible to reduce the size of the box walls, but they do make it feel quite rugged. Currently in my Jeep, it rides underneath the emergency brake until I need to use it. It will also site higher up in front of the emergency brake but my original intention was to make it easily slide on and off of the emergency brake handle. As also mentioned, I did not pre-drill any holes for screws. I drilled a pilot hole in each corner and that appears to suffice.
aBitOWhit

title: Flexible PLA guide for Type A Machine Printer

description.text: This guide goes between the pinch wheels and the aluminum block of the Type A Machines Series 1 printer to prevent flexible PLA from not feeding properly.  I was getting a lot of "mis-feeds" where the flexible filament was not stiff enough to be pushed through the extruder.

I printed this using PLA and have had no issues leaving it installed when running flexible PLA or traditional PLA.  I ran a 5/64" drill bit through the filament hole to cleanup some deformation I got when it was printed.

Notes:

Printing at a higher resolution reduces friction and improves layer adhesion. May initially make creaking noises while the rubbing parts wear in but should quiet down quickly. I printed with PLA plastic without rafts, using blue painters tape on my unheated bed. Requires ZERO post processing if printed directly on the bed. Printed part should be 1.285" long and about .65" wide at the base. Took about 45 minutes per piece at .1mm layer height.

(printed part in blue On left) Accurately reproduces the fit of the original (white part On right). Print the hinge half in this orientation and you won't need support overhangs. (leave space between hinge pieces if printing more than one) both Hinge pieces installed in the open position reused the original holes and positions, Reinstalled on the cooler.

I use Autodesk Inventor at work for punch/laser and forming into final products, and have become fairly adept at modeling parts for 3D printing. I measured and modeled the original part, then over/undersized points of contact and interference between hinge halves by ~.3mm since that seems to provide a precise fit in my designs. As originally molded, the part was optimal for 3d printing with the hinge mounting surface down, since there weren't any significant overhangs at angles less than 45 degrees. So no tweaks or supports were needed to make it fit.

print_settings.Notes:: Print in high resolution in PLA, if using an FDM printer. The overhangs on the glass thread are unavoidably harsh, so you should choose your materials and settings to optimise for good overhang performance.

description.text:
Use common glass pepsi and coke bottles with your sodastream to make smaller servings, without any plastic flavour. This adaptor, based on LaurentWeb's excellent concept, is completely food safe, by mounting the bottle rim directly in to the sodastream gasket - none of the printed plastic is exposed to fluid or gas. Most other glass bottles with a screw top use this thread, including some larger bottles. This adaptor provides a good way to upgrade a cheap sodastream to use glass bottles. Print at home in PLA, or buy one on shapeways and help support me.

Print a SodaStream_Glass_Pepsi_Adapter.stl and screw it on to the top of a glass bottle, so the glass of the bottle protrudes a little from the the adapter, then screw the bottle in to a sodastream. You shouldn't have removal problems, but just in case, two notches are included to aid in unscrewing if it somehow gets jammed in to the sodastream's socket.

Known compatible bottles:

  • Pepsi 300ml (sold in Australia in IGA and some supermarkets)
  • Coke 330ml (sold in Australia in most major supermarkets)

Warning: Soda bottles are designed with compression in mind. You may risk glass explosion if you use bottles that weren't originally designed to hold carbonated drinks

If you'd like to build remixes, the Glass Pepsi Bottle Top Reference.stl provides an accurate reproduction of the top of a 300ml Glass Pepsi bottle. The Glass Pepsi Bottle Top Cutting Tool.stl version is expanded with 0.5mm of tolerance in every dimension, so you can simply boolean difference it out of another object to provide a suitable screw hole. I release both of these files under Creative Commons Attribution.

title: Manivelle établi pliant / Crank for a folding workbench
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
English:
One of the crank handle of my folding workbench was broken. Even if this is a cheap one, it is still cheaper to repair it instead of to buy a new one. And moreover it is funnier to design it yourself, and more convenient to replace when it breaks on a Sunday.

The design is a fairly faithful reproduction of the original crank, with a mechanical more adapted (but not optimized) to the 3D print constraints. This is an assembly of two parts. I used a M5 screw/nut to replace the pin in order to ease a future disassembly if it breaks again, but you can obviously re-use the pin.

Update: Added a more robust V2

Français:
Une des manivelles de mon établi pliant était cassé. Même si c'est du matériel low cost, c'est tout de même moins cher de le réparer que d'en racheter un. C'est d'ailleurs plus fun à dessiner soi-même, et plus pratique à remplacer quand ça casse un dimanche.

Le dessin est une reproduction visuellement assez fidèle de la manivelle originale, avec une mécanique adaptée (mais pas optimisée) pour les contraintes de l'impression 3D. C'est un assemblage d'une bielle et une manivelle. J'ai utilisé une vis/écrou en M5 pour remplacer la goupille afin de faciliter le démontage si ça casse, mais vous pouvez évidement ré-utiliser la goupille d'origine.

Update : Ajout d'une V2 plus robuste

Printer:

Dagoma DiscoEasy200

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

50

Notes:

English:
The handle can be printed as-is, without support.
The other part should be printed as placed by default into the STL file, adding support below and a raft to help the supports (there are a lot) to stick the plate. In this position, the supported layer is not visible when the whole thing is assembled on the workbench.

Français:
Pour la manivelle, vous pouvez l'imprimer telle quelle, sans support.
Pour la bielle, je conseille la position par défaut du STL, en plaçant des supports en dessous et un raft pour aider l'accroche des supports car il y en a un paquet. Dans cette position, la partie supportée n'est pas visible une fois le tout assemblé sur l'établi.

description.text:
This was a concept I did on Nikolai Tesla's famous one-way valve with no moving parts. Tesla's original idea was 2D and planer. This takes the concept and makes it circular.

This is a bit of a work in progress. Even from the original idea max efficiency is about 20-30% so its hard to evaluate if it actually works or not. I think from blowing in it there is a difference. I cut it in half to make it more 3D printer friendly.

CFD shows a 20% efficiency difference between out versus in. If this gets any interest I'll post the visualizations.

comments.text: You should find that the amount of resistance of the valve more-or-less squares with the velocity of the fluid being pushed through it. Also, because the is essentially just 1 valve it may not be that effective. I believe Tesla originally said that it would take 7 valves in series to create sufficient resistance to create a total blockage (or one way valve).
comments.author: mozgorazrushitel

comments.text: Yeah, even the original concept at low flow rates the difference wasn't dramatic. Was a good youtube video showing that as you increase flow rate the differences between the directions becomes more pronounced
comments.author: mozgorazrushitel

comments.text: How do you actuate the valve on this? I'm guessing through a variable input flow?
comments.author: BoyDrone

comments.text: If you read Tesla's original patent, there is no actuator / moving parts. Essential there is hysteresis, blow in one way and it flows 1 l/min to make a number up and blow in the other it flows .8 l/min (I don't know the actual number for this valve). Each repeat of the valve increases this hysteresis ie (1 l/min one way might be .5 l/min the other). Tesla suggested you could get to a large hysteresis with a good design and enough loops.

title: Master Sword (Full Size) - Legend of Zelda BotW / OoT / SS

description.text:
Remix from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1449187

I removed some of the details from Twilight Princess artworks to make it almost identical to the one in Breath of the Wild and Ocarina of Time. Should also be more similar to the Skyward Sword one.

I've fixed the handle wrapping so that it continues until the end instead of being cut for some reason.

I've also added a big hole inside all the blade parts and a smaller one for the handle parts. This way not only I could save more PLA, but I could also add metal inserts to make the whole structure more resilient.

Lastly I've added a version where the blade is completely separated from the handle (Guard_edit_v2 and Forte_0_for_guard_v2), so it's easier to paint and also to print. I've also included the combined version from the original file (of course with the previously mentioned edits).

All the parts without "_edit" in the name have not been edited.

EDIT: As it has been requested, I've added a version of the handle and the pommel without the fake plastic wrap, in order to allow an addition of a leather wrap.

description.text:
This neutrino wand is based off the wonderful model by DancinFool82. There were a number of modifications I wanted to make to reduce filament used in printing and allow the use of 3/4 inch PVC pipe for the handles. I'm making a proton pack for my son and the handles need to be smaller.

I've split the main base to make it easier to print with minimal support. There are small guides modeled inside so the side panel will be easier to glue on. I've added a new mounting peg for the rear handle that has a base piece that slides on before the PVC pipe. This looks more like the original prop to me. The bottom base plate has been redone to allow the use of M2 screws to put it together. There are screw mounts in the main base and side pieces. This will allow access to the electronics after it's put together.

The front handle parts have been reduced a little in size to match the smaller 3/4 inch pipe handle. For an adult I think 3/4 inch PVC is better anyway as it feels better in my hands as well. All of the parts have been cleaned up and checked for errors as well. I was having some issues printing some of the original parts.

I did not include the clippard valve. I'm using this one which is great
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2286284

Update: 6/5/17
I've added a new main box (gunbox_main_updated.stl) which fixes a couple of issues and adds an internal mount for a 10 and 5 led bargraph. The display area will work with 14 leds. Also updated the clear tube adapter and end piece so they are now sized for a 25mm clear tube

Update 6/15/2017
More improvements to the gunbox. The front lip on the bargraph area is reduced and there is a cutout to bring the bargraph closer to the surface.

Update 7/21/2017
I'm finishing up the build of this. I'm making 2 of them. One for my son who's a lefty, so everything is reversed, and one for my wife. Added a photo of the lefty version ready for final assembly

Update 8/10/2017

  • Removed the old base plate and gun track and replaced with a combined model with more detail. Should look better and be stronger

  • Added a new gunbox_main that has a thicker roof area. This improves strength in that spot where I've had some breakage.

Update 8/25/17

  • Remodeled the gunbox_front_valve.stl and gunbox_back_handle_valve.stl files to be higher quality

The bottom base model has some circles on the edges that rip off easily after printing to keep it from warping because my slicer wouldn't add a brim.

Printing at .3 for all parts took about 24 hours. I've printed a lot of prototypes so it's hard to say for sure. It all came out really well though.

PVC Tube Requirements

3/4 inch PVC pipe is used for the handles.

rear handle:
45 degree angle on one side
length: 188mm (7.4 inches)

front handle:
162.5mm

Clear Tube

I found some clear plastic test tubes on amazon for pretty cheap. They have a slight taper but when cut it's not noticeable.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01MCYNVRV

I will be using these for the clear area. They have a 25mm - 24.5mm exterior diameter. I'll be updating the front parts soon once they are modified to support it.

print_settings.Notes:: The posts on my 15 year old garage sale hardwood cabinet started to disintegrate with age.  I love the cabinets but hated that the doors wouldn't stay shut.  I use Inventor at work to model laser/punch/formed metal parts and have become pretty adept at modeling 3D printed parts when things break around the house..  So I measured and modeled up replacement parts that I could use to directly replace the existing molded parts.  The hardest part was tweaking the pincer-grip of the base, as the original modeled part was too firm and inflexible, so it was hard to close and open.  Adding a 15 degree face draft inward to both edges was the trick needed to make it have a similar feel and retention pressure when closing the door.  When printed in the correct orientation, no rafts or supports needed.   The clip base  with the in-cut side facing up, the clip with the pincers facing up and the post with the large side down. I use blue painters tape on my unheated bed and PLA plastic.  Slots in the clip-base allow a small bit of alignment up or down and the slot of the clip itself auto-aligns if the post is off a few 16ths of an inch.  The center of the clip could be mounted with a screw through the included, recessed hole (Maybe a #6 or #8 pan head screw) , but this would negate the self alignment feature.

description.text: The clip and clip-base require a small flat-head screwdriver or knife to assemble. start it at an angle and work the retainer clips over the edge. They fit together one-way. Should work best with #8 screws. The post needs about 1" long screw, the base, a pair of 1/2" to 3/4" long screws

description.text:
I love the tri-spinners and I have made them for many people. I just don't like having to use 4 608 bearings for each spinner with 3 of them just used as counterweights. I found that 1/2 inch nuts have about the same weight/size as a 608 bearing, so I modified the spinner to use them for counterweights.

I also modified the the knurling in the scad file to have not have partial knurling on the edges. I am a bit of a perfectionist.

This project is a remix of my other spinner but the nuts and bearing caps are flush.

Requires:

  • 1x 608 bearing
  • 3x 1/2" nuts

Everything press fits without glue. Enjoy!

title: Dog Doo Bag Holder with bone-shaped cutout

description.text: This one tightly loops through a standard mesh leash to stay put near the end of the leash. I borrowed the rubber cap from my old but broken dog bag holder I bought years ago.. Since most dog bags unroll from the outside, not the center, this makes it easier to pull dog bags out yet they don't unroll easily by accident. A pin in the middle of the dog bone cutout makes it so you don't need any supports when printing. Just cut out with a pair of side-cutters and gently sand the edge smooth (So it doesn't pierce bags while extracting.) Fits standard dog bag holder refills available from all retailers (Publix, Wal Mart, Petsmart, etc..) These usually have about 21 bags per roll.

Customized version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2325330

Created with Customizer! http://www.thingiverse.com/apps/customizer/run?thing_id=2325330
This idea is a training device for surgical skills in laparoscopic technique learning.
The model consist in a table or bed about 15 x 15 cm x 1 cm with some pins about 30 mm height, spaces about 30mm and some lines side to side. this object go into the pelvitrainer and the student use some O rings to put and change hand to hand with the videolaparoscopic instruments and increase your skills and coordination hand - eye, and 2D monitor. On this manner they can to increased and advance in your learning curve.

PINES AND O RINGS FOR ENDOSCOPIC SURGICAL LEARNING
The curve learning for surgeons in the videosurgery is difficult and long consuming time. The 2 D vision of the video image don't have the deep dimension and requeire some sikills to coordinate the eyes with your hands and the 2 D monitor. For this exercises the learning surgeon need to accumulate hours of practice how airplane pilots in simulators.
i look the possibility with the elegible objects to create a device to increase abilities for surgeon in training.
i uploads the objet, put in creator and customaze it changing measures and look about the results until find the best prototype. i have any experience with design program but was pleasure to start this amazing learning course, that open my mind about many possibilities in my career.
i need  to add  some lines of pins  for  my model to complete the design   i don't  know  how  tools need  for  this  changes. i believe  with increase my skills  the would make that.

description.text: The plastic clip surrounding the metal key used to open the door (And attach the key to a key ring) was broken completely. It took about 17 attempts before I came up with a usable result. This so far lasted over a year in my pocket before I traded my car in. The keys were identical between my 2005 and 2008 models, so it should fit anything between those two years, possibly more. Don't need to glue the halves together, but do so if you need.. The two halves slide together and the key ring holds it together. Print with the openings up as showin in the above photos and you won't need any supports. I use blue painter's tape on an unheated bed with PLA plastic. Let the parts fully cool before removing from the bed, so that they don't warp any. .1mm will make it so smooth you won't notice ridges. Zero post-printing process needed

print_settings.Notes:: The parts in the photos are PLA test parts, but I strongly recommend PETG or ABS.  If you print in an enclosure or your motors run hot, a PLA motor mount WILL warp, and soon.

description.text:
UPDATE 2017-05-26:
I neglected to give dimensions for the 2040 extrusion:
475mm if you use the printed tensioner
490mm if you use the metal tensioner assembly
These are minimum lengths. A 500mm piece from OpenBuilds would work fine as-is for both.

I've uploaded pics and spec drawing of a metal tensioner assembly. It takes 20-30mm off the total width of the printer.
My prototype in the photos is shorter than the drawing because the 2040 beam was already cut.
You'll need:
Qty1 20x60x5mm Aluminum or steel stock - those dimensions can be fiddled a bit
Qty1 eccentric spacer
Qty1 idler pulley of your choice, with 5mm bore. The one in the photos is 20T.
Qty1 5mm ID, 7mm OD shim
Qty1 5mm washer or another shim
Qty1 M5x25mm screw
Qty2 M5 nuts
Qty2 M5x10mm screws
Qty2 M5 Tee nuts

The Anet's stock X rail assembly just isn't rigid enough to support a direct extruder. I found Gavin's excellent 20x20 conversion, but already had a pile of OpenBuild 2040 V-Slot on hand, so I adapted. You'll need his X-Carriage_Belt_Tensioner.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2088574

The Z limit switch mount is half of Kureigu's endstop Thing:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1443052

If you're keeping the stock extruder and hotend, you'll need a metal bracket for proper heat dissipation. The simplest solution uses OpenBuild's gantry plate and standard wheels, and drill the stock extruder bracket to fit the gantry plate. You'll need

Qty 1: OB 80x20 gantry plate
Qty 4: OB wheel kits
Screw sets to attach the Anet extruder bracket to the gantry plate
The Belt Clamp and Belt Clamp Plate Things. The Clamp Thing includes parts for both left and right side attachment, but you only need one.

Or:
The included gantry plate STL is designed to use a common steel right-angle NEMA17 bracket with the stock extruder parts. You'll need:

Qty 4: OpenBuild mini wheel kits
Qty 1: This bracket (they're available everywhere, pick your vendor):
https://smile.amazon.com/dp/B01HHPD7LY
Qty1: 22mm 3x0.50mm screw
Qty2: 25mm 3x0.50mm screws
The FanMountPlate and FanMountBase Things to mount the part fan

The X rails and lead screws are spaced 17mm center to center. This conversion should work on some Tronxy P802x models and any Prusa i3 clone with the same 17mm spacing.

The Bowden conversion in the photos is a separate remix, which I'll publish eventually

Customized Anet A8

title: Toyota Auris phone stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
My new Toyota Auris MY17 comes without a phone holder suitable for the size of today's smartphones. The only place I can keep it, is in the cans holder or in the closed compartments.
So I've replaced the central cans holder divider with a phone stand.
I've designed three version, two for iPhone6/7, with and without original Apple protective cover, and one presumably universal.
The iPhone stand can accommodate the phone only in a vertical position. The one intended for naked iPhone can safely hold the phone upside-down without damaging the camera lens.
The universal one can hold any size up to 10 mm in thickness, in vertical or horizontal position.

Disclaimer:
This phone stand is not intended for a phone to be used with the screen running, such as for monitoring the vehicle parameters with an OBD link, because its location distracts the driver by putting him under risk for himself and for others.
So, use this stand only for phones which should not be watched while driving.

También necesitaba un ventilador de capa radial, con en ventilador de 40 X 40 mm. situado en la parte trasera del carro X y a la vez fijado al soporte del sensor capacitivo de 18 mm. y el ventilador del extrusor, con corriente de aire bien canalizado sin afectar al bloque calefactor, también de 40x40 mm.
Este carro y sus componentes es compatible con todas las impresoras 3D del tipo prusa i3 y similares que dispongan un carro X con una distancia de 45 mm. +/- 1mm. entre centros de guías de 8 mm de diametro.
El prototipo tenia algunos pequeños fallos; pero ya están corregidos en los archivos de descarga..
El Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_JO420OvWlo

It is the complete X-car. It is an adaptation to my needs and to the extruders (E3D v5) that to my best work for me. I also needed a radial fan, with a fan 40 X 40 mm. And the fan of the extruder, with air flow well channeled without affecting the heating block, also of 40x40 mm.

My Filter Queen Vacuum is several decades old. I bought it used in 2005 and even then, it showed only a tad bit of wear and tear. Well... dog hair got jammed up in the wheel bearings on the riveted-in-place caster wheels, and the wheel eventually crumbled since the rubber had died long ago. This wasn't a perfect print, being an early thing I made.. but it fit and works perfectly, so I stopped tweaking on it. After removing the hair and clearing off all the rubber bits stuck to the shaft collar, I was able to clip two of these wheels on my vacuum and am still using it 2 years later! Wheels rotate perfectly and the gap from the print shrinking in the corners during the build don't affect that at all. Don't even hear it when it rolls! The screws are #6 pan head sheet metal. I think they were 1" in length. Print two halves with the axis pointing vertically or horizontally, and print 4 of the pins with the axis vertical. The pins help align the two wheel halves. Rotate the halves so that 2 screws go in one side and the other two screws in the opposite direction on the other side. shouldn't require drafts or supports. I nearly lost the print by running out of filament, but was able to clip it off and substitute another color without stopping, which is why one of the wheels is both blue and white.

title: Moto Z Car vent mount + Source Files! (Solidworks)

description.text:
Designed this as a "moto mod" car vent mount for my Moto Z. Should work in Moto Z Play too, since the moto mods are in the same shape.

I used 20x10x2 mm magnets that i bought from Aliexpress some time ago. They are really strong, but since they are some millimiters away from the phone (because of the printing layers), they do not attach ultra-strong agains the phone. If you are going to use weak magnets, make them closer to the phone (but watch out if they dont rip the layers off when you force to separate).

There is a feature that is really missing! In the center of the gold connectors there is a central pin that is used for centralizing the moto mod. I could not add this without adding huge supports. A two-pice shell would be perfect...... One just with the centralizing pin...

Dimensional are quite good. There are 2mm missing in the bottom. If you are obssesed with perfection, fell free to work on it...

title: PVC Fittings for Hoop House style Greenhouse

description.text:
These are 1/2 " PVC Fittings I designed to put together a Hoop House style Greenhouse. You could probably use furniture grade pvc fittings to build this, but I wanted screw holes designed into the parts. I did not put screw holes in the corner fittings as I didn't screw any of the 3 full length (hoop) pieces together, just all of the cut to length pieces were drilled and screwed.

The photo with the plants has these exact parts being used, but the one with just the pipes on the pallet has earlier designs. I needed to make some changes for strength reasons, as I broke some of the smaller/clip on style fittings. The pallet is just one I picked up for free a few years ago. You can make a frame with 2x4s and drill holes for the pvc to fit in. I put the pallet on a frame with caster wheels so I can move it around the yard as needed.

I bought 4' long snap clamps and cut them down into smaller pieces to clip on the insect netting and plastic. Good price here: http://www.greenhousemegastore.com/product/snap-clamps/pvc-fittings

Please check out my other things, I will be uploading more of the designs I have worked on over the last couple years.

I created this model using Blender while following along with the tutorial linked below:

https://youtu.be/JjW6r10Mlqs

This was my first Blender creation. I highly recommend this tutorial if you're just getting started and want an easy project. I had to pause and replay the video at a couple of points to get a clear understanding of what controls to use at various points, but, in the end, I figured it out.

Two of the "gotchas" I encountered while working on this model were solved by "removing doubles" (i.e. removing accidentally doubled-up model components which kept some of the tools from working) and by "rebuilding normals" (i.e. resetting the lighting on the model if it looked like it became turned inside-out.

I recommend scaling the model up to at least 50mm in height before printing, and a few light supports will need to be added for effective printing (under the body, trunk, ears, and tail).

description.text:
This was designed to replace the starter recoil pulley on a chainsaw. It is customizable in OpenSCAD to meet your needs. The current STL should fit most major chainsaws and blowers from craftsman/poulan etc. that use 4 pieces to ratchet the starter.

I take no responsibility for use with machinery, please print at your own risk. I printed in TOUGH RESIN with a FormLabs Form 2 SLA Printer at an angle to reduce potential shearing. I would not suggest using PLA in this application for heat and rigidity.

It is a fun object to make.

Back with another 3 position cam mount. This time for the Lumenier QAV-R. (and similar) Its designed to fit around the front standoffs. Use MIDDLE side plate holes for proper angles.

Positionable on the fly at 10, 25, or 40 degrees.

This fits lens with 17.5mm outside diameter (most 2.1 or 2.5 lenses)

Two different versions, see pics:
Full Notch will work with no mods to the QAV-R. It slips over the front of the standoffs. Probably will still have to take top plate off due to the lens holes being slightly compression fit to hold the cam steady.

Not Fully Notched is exactly the same except it slides over the standoffs and makes for a more secure fit. You will have to sand about 1mm from the front of the side plates in order for them to fit correctly in the top and bottom plate.

Honestly, I dont think the fully notched version will come off, even in a bad crash, but it was easy to design a fully enclosed version, so why not? Two options, choose what works best.

Self watering pot

  • NOTE* The real picture has a smaller watering hole than the file has

You will need to purchase this LED Lamp from Amazon:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B005HF3ULY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

You will also need (8) M3x8mm pan head screws.

Supports are not necessary but you might want to add a couple to support the button and power cord holes on the base. I did not purchase the power cord as I just use batteries to power the lamp.

Each picture that you convert to a Lithophane will need to be cropped before conversion.
It must be 110mm X 110mm square.

You can convert photographs to a printable lithophane by uploading it to:
http://3dp.rocks/lithophane/
Here is a great tutorial on how to prepare your photgraphs, convert and then print.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KRdMwuBQQ0U

Be sure to change the settings for each conversion to:
Maximum size = 110mm
Positive Image
Leave the thickness at 3mm.

I used a 2mm border but your preferences may vary.

Once you have the base printed, you will need to disassemble the LED lamp and remove it's cover. Peel back the rubber feet from the bottom and remove the 4 screws. They are not needed for the base you will print. There are 4 tabs that snap into place that secure it well enough without using the screws.

Before installing the base onto the lamp you will need to attach the frame to the top of the base using 4 M3x8 screws. I made the holes a touch bigger to make sure you didn't have to force the screw in. So be sure not to over tighten so you don't strip them out. Mine were perfect and held everything tight.

Once the screws inside the base have been installed you can attach the base to the lamp fixture. Be sure to install the button into the button hole and hold it in a way that it doesn't slide out before installing. Once installed the button will be secured and can't fall out. Make sure you install the base in the correct position so that the button lines up with the side of the light switch on the lamp fixture.

Gently slide each lithophane into the grooves from the top of the frame. Make sure they seat against the base.
Then install the lid onto the frame. Be sure that each lithophane is seated in the grooves on the lid as well. If printed properly everything should seat perfectly. Secure the lid to the frame using (4) M3x8 screws.

I printed this in Wood PLA. Whatever filament you use, you must make sure that there is no warping of the parts while printing or they will not fit properly.

I hope the directions are clear enough to understand.
If not please ask any questions and I will answer them asap.

Enjoy!

title: Moon Rocket for single extruder printer (adhesive-free assembly)

description.text:
Rocket for single extruder printer. All parts snap together for easy, glue-less assembly. Could be treated as a simple puzzle. Once fully assembled the rocket stands approximately 173.08 mm tall.

May or may not require minor fitting depending how accurate and consistent your print is. Has 0.2 to 0.3mm clearance between parts in most places.

Printing quantities and suggested colors:
A-NoseCone: 1x Red.
B-5Stage: 2x Red, 2x White (top level)
C-4Stage: 2x Red, 2x White
D-3Stage: 2x Red, 2x White
E-2Stage: 2x Red, 2x White
F-1Stage: 2x Red, 2x White (bottom level)
G-Base: 1x Red (requires support enabled)
H-Center: 2x (not visible, color does not matter)
A-NoseConePrintAid (Print this one along with A-NoseCone. This will force your printer to move back and forth between the two parts, giving time for the thinner layers at the tip of the nose cone to cool before another layer is laid on top, giving better results. )

All parts will print best if laid in the upright position on the printer bed.

B to F can be difficult and time consuming to put back in the correct order if they get mixed up. It is recommended to keep them organized until assembly.

This rocket is inspired by a German V2 test rocket.

UPDATE
After noticing that a lot of people like to print this rocket as big as possible I have added STL files for the base with separate dovetailed legs. These files have been named with the "G2" prefix. This should allow people to print even larger rockets. However be advised that the dovetails for the legs have been created with zero clearance. Some fitting will most likely be required for assembly.

UPDATE 2
I have noticed that many prints have a problem with a gap between the nose cone and the side panels. I believe that the cause of that is that with the way the nose cone, central pieces and base fit together there is a fraction of a millimeter of length being added at every joint. These tiny differences stack up to a noticeable gap when the side panels are added. The size of this gap can vary with different prints.

I have printed a 200% scale rocket and have assembled the base, middle pieces and nose cone without putting on the side panels first and measured the vertical space that the center pieces must occupy with a vernier caliper (should be 65mm at 100% size). I have noticed a 0.7% dimension discrepancy in mine so I have resized all my center pieces by stretching them by 0.7% in height in my slicer program. Everything fitted flush with zero gap after that.

For better fit I would recommend measuring your partially completed rocket and adjusting the height of your side panels in consequence just like I did.

author: JvdP

title: OHG - 800°C BBQ Grill - Top Heat Grill aka BEEF O MATIC

description.text:
OHG - 800°C BBQ Grill - Top Heat Grill

Important!
This is nothing for your 3d printer! The provided STL files are just for visualization. No need to download the STL files, instead download just the ZIP file for all files!

Warning!
For outdoor use only!
Warning: accessible parts may be very hot. Keep children and pets away from the
barbecue.
Do not attempt to move the barbecue during use.
Turn off the gas supply at the gas cylinder after use.
Leak test the barbecue before first use, annually, when dismantled, when parts are
replaced, or if the gas cylinder is removed or replaced

Use at your own risk!!!

Introduction:

Since I saw the first time a top heat grill, I always wanted to have one but the high price scared me so I had to look for alternatives. I found this forum, which is a german based gril forum and they have this thread helping each other to build one themselfes.

https://www.grillsportverein.de/forum/forums/eigenbauten.56/

The main thread was closed because of some dumb ass, sucking out the information from the community and turning it into making money. They didn`t know how to use CAD software but they got help a lot. But if you ask them for the drawings they wanted to have money or they were trying to sell you the metall sheet parts instead. This is bull shit therefore I just started to merge all information from the threads into my design and now I am realising it to everybody. From the community for the community!

If you are not aware what this grill does, look into google for the german word "Oberhitzegrill".

Files:

You receive today all my work on this project, including

Inventor Files
Exported Step Files
DXF files for sending it directly to your laser cutter
PDF files for better overview
STL files again: just for visualization

Versions:

Blank Version
For fully customization, the dxf files are missing since this version is a not ready to cut version.

Minimal Version
If you just want a funtional top heat grill

Modern Version
This version looks much more nicer. Cost difference at the laser cutter are 50€.

Material:
All parts are laser cut parts.
Important: All parts are cut and designed for 3 mm V2A stainless sheet metall except part E-1004-01 & E-1005-01. This two parts are from 1,5 mm V2A stainless sheet metall.
I have used following company to have my stuff lasser cut:

http://www.geerscutting.com/

If you are from Germany, you should use them. They are by far the cheapest company out there.

Material number identification:

E-1XXX-XX
Should not be touched except you have a different burner

E-2XXX-XX
Are for custimization

E-oXoo-oo
Is the index number for the version:
0 = Blank
1 = Minimal
2 = Modern

E-ooXo-oo
Is the index number for variation

E-oooX-oo
Is the index number for part

E-oooo-XX
Revision number so far 00

Folding parts:

Following parts need to be folded acordingly:
E-1004-01
E-1005-01
E-XXX7-01

You should go to your local mechanic have them let it made.

The burner:
The design is for a gas heater from the company Rothenberger Industrial. It is the ECO version 2270 with Piezzo ignition. Drawing are attached to check if you can get a similiar gas heater in your country. At this point: I will not make any custimization for any other heaters!

Update:
I am still waiting for the folded parts in the meanwhile I have assembled the feet on the ground plate and the heat burner is also assembled.

Additional parts needed:
4x knurled nut "long version" to use as feet (DIN ISO 466)
4x press in nuts M6
12x M6 washer
8x M6x16 screws
4x M6 nuts
12x M5x16 F screws (DIN ISO 7380)
12x M5 nuts (DIN ISO 934)

consider to use here also the small parts made out of stainless steel

Assembly:
I have currently not the equipment to make an assembly video of the parts and the burner. Tip me and I might consider it in future.
So far, you can use following video for instruction:

./watch?v=cq3Ygv2qFSM

FAQ:

none at this point

Important! If you like the design please consider to support my work with a small tip thru this website. Thanks!

ToDos:

Upload pictures of my top heat grill (waiting for folded parts)
detailed parts list
a more detailed assembly file

title: MRBG (Modular Rubber Band Gun)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
/!\ WARNINGS FOR STUPID/LITIGIOUS PEOPLE: Rubber band gun intended for recreational purposes. Do not use in public. If shooting someone with rubber band guns, make sure they are sufficiently protected. I am not liable for any damages resulting from improper use of this rubber band gun. /!\

This is my first ever rubber band gun made of Lego. Primarily focused on modularity, the MRBG (Modular Rubber Band Gun) is split into seven units: the pistol (core module), rifle barrel, stock, prop magazine, prop scope, magazine, and mag extensions (for use with rifle barrel). The mechanism is not mine, but is essentially copied from this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r3Xs-gbThss
The prop magazine can fold in half to look like a larger caliber mag, and there is another prop magazine for the pistol. This prop mag attaches to the bottom of the handle and stores inside of it when unused. You will need an average sized rubber band to spring the trigger.

STATS
Fire mode: automatic
Fire mechanism: repeater wheel regulated by escapement connected to sliding bolt
Capacity: ~6 rounds (~3 rounds with mag extension)
Ammo: size 18 rubber bands

MODES
Pistol (scope optional)
Machine pistol (pistol + pistol mag)
Pump action shotgun (pistol + rifle barrel) (stock optional)
SMG (pistol + mag) (stock optional)
Assault rifle (pistol + rifle barrel + mag) (stock and scope optional)
Sniper rifle (pistol + rifle barrel + stock + scope + folded mag)

FEATURES
Prop pistol mag can be stored in handle
Magazine pin attaches to bolt when not in use (see "MRBG" .lxf file)
Handguard attached to underside of rifle barrel (also serves as mock pump for shotgun)
Bolt handle can switch sides to match user's handedness
Working safety on magazine
Prop magazine can be folded for use in "sniper" mode (see "MRBG Assembled" .lxf file)
Magazine extensions are stored in unfolded prop magazine (see "MRBG" .lxf file)
Spring-assisted mag ejection (for speedy ejection, tip gun back and release pin)

Credit to Ironkilix for his mechanism and initial design.

remixed_from.author: Gear_Down_For_What
remixed_from.title: Modular Robotic Arm, Hinge Joint, No Hardware

description.text:
Updates:
11/13/17 - uploaded the longer version, do not make one section of the arm out of the longer parts and the other out of the original length, the program will not be able to solve for that.

Youtube Video!

EZER Build by Old Farm Hand! - https://youtu.be/YoQsGiXItqQ

  • Torque Testing the new design with the 66:1 https://youtu.be/YyoCF6DXfvI

Features:

  1. This is a redesign of the EZ print robotic arm, more info can be found on that page than this one.
  2. Less parts, no hardware needed to hold the joint together.
  3. Ring holders have anti-backlash models where the grip teeth are rotated 1 degree.
  4. Much more solid
  5. This version requires no hardware except 3mm bolts to hold the steppers on.

Where's Everything Else???

https://www.thingiverse.com/Gear_Down_For_What/collections/robotic-arm
In this collection you will find:
  • All other related parts for this project
  • Future updates to this Project
  • All user submitted remix's
  • Click that watch button to get notifications on future uploads!

Special Instructions For The Gearbox(s):

1.) Pick your favorite gearbox from the collection
2.) Print out all 4 ring gears, the "4 Module planet gears", the "One piece sun" and "Sun gear #4"

  • The Gearboxes that are to be used with this joint are located in the "Robotic Arm" collection.
  • Don't get confused by other similar gearboxes that I have made, if they are compatible, they will be listed in the collection, link is above.
  • The gearboxes are used to support the joint, like emmets gear bearing, but they also drive the joint, so they are necessary!

Drive motors

  • Nema 17 for all
  • Don't buy cheap Nema 17 motors, they will get hot and melt the gears!

A and B?

  • The "Rotating Base" is an "A" style connection, so the "B" Style joint gets mounted to it, so on and so forth.
  • Connections with a stepper motor mount are considered "A" Style connections.
  • It's an unavoidable compatibility problem that arose from the recent simplification of the design. Opposite's attract, A only connects to B and B only connects to A. yada yada.

Compatibility With Other Designs

This Design is only compatible with the "EZ Print" design if you understand the "A" and "B". The major downfall being that with the EZ Print design, each section of arm had a "A" style end and a "B" style end. This new design has two "A" Style ends on one section, and two "B" style ends on the other section. For that reason, be careful if deciding to use these parts in combination with the others. If you have an "A" section meeting up to another "A" section the arm will have a sideways offset of 10 mm. This newer design also ended up 1mm longer per section (center of gearbox to center to gearbox) than previous designs.

Bendy Bend Bend:

This arm rotates 230 degrees before colliding with itself in the cad program but it is actually more like 229 degrees real life.

Other Important Info:

Electronics, Firmware?!?
  • Program that I use is here: https://github.com/GearDownForWhat/RobotArm
  • I run this on an Arduino DUE with a CNC shield and DRV8825 Stepper drivers, Arduino MEGA "might" also work for this.
  • Arduino Due A000062
  • CNC Shield Expansion Board with drv8825 Stepper Motor Drivers
  • Nema 17 Steppers I used for J0 and J1
  • Smaller (cheaper) Steppers and Optional Wires For Cheaper and Smaller Steppers
CAD Files??

  • I Included the Fusion 360 Project with this, But the most recent version of this project can be downloaded in lots of different formats from this link: http://a360.co/2viZyW5
    and the longer version at this link: http://a360.co/2iTdWva

  • Feel free to create your own modifications and parts for this project, and if you do, make sure you create a remix and upload them, then I'll add them to my main collection so the whole community can share them! Thanks!
Show Your Work!
  • Make a "make" and show everyone what you made! (make? :0) Everyone will thank you for it!

For More Cool Projects and Upgrades, Don't forget to Follow Me on Thingiverse and Subscribe to my Youtube Channel

Gear Down For What?

remixed_from.title: Wanhao i3 BLTouch Mount for v2.1

title: Wanhao i3 V2.1 BLTouch Mount (with LED)

description.text:
This is a remix of rativiv's design with LED mount, low profile and slightly bigger curve (optimized for ABS shrinkage).

Marlin config:
X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 7
Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 50
Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 0

changes:
-Low profile. BLtouch is very light, you don't need the upper part, plus my wanhao bearing mount does not have "free" holes on the top side. So I cut the top part and made it compatible with most (all? some? ) belt tension mods.
-Curve is larger, tested to print OK in ABS.
-There was a 1layer gap before the bltouch mount which I fixed. (strange - maybe autodesk messed it up).
-The BLtouch mount is moved upwards. There is more room to play with how low it sits. You will probably need washers and/or nuts though for the original BLtouch. Rativiv's design was almost spot on for me.
-The BLtouch mount has been slightly reworked so it can easily be printed when the model is sideways. Holes are the same.
-optional LED mount
-I altered the model around the fixing (bottom) holes to print better in my printer with 0.4mm nozzle.

LED mount
For 5mm LED with common LED holder (http://tomsha.com/shop/images/LED-Mount-1pc.jpg).
You can also hot glue the LED without any base.

File details:
noLED_LowProfile : no LED mount
2xLED_LowProfile : with LED mount
2xLED_wShade_LowProfile : with LED mount, with bottom/top/side shade

Diffuser: A small diffuser for the "wShade" part, useful if you LEDs are too bright, your bed is reflective and your camera sucks.

ps.
BLtouch on the photos is the original, May 2017 version, "Smart v1.0"

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The files with LED Shade, should be printed on the side.
Those without, can be printed standing up or on their side.

PLA/PETG
0.3mm, 50% infill, 3 perimeters. Prefer PETG, PLA is too brittle. Top of the curve and the 2-wall (0.8mm) part will break off easily.
The curve will be slightly larger than needed. But it will work ok. Try it out without scaling it.

ABS
0.3mm, 20% infill, 2 perimeters with supports on the small holes if you want them to be perfect. It is not necessary though.

The basic files do not include and weight reduction and take a lot longer to print but they will be a lot easier for you to edit if you want to change anything.

Materials needed:

-2 velcro straps
-4 M3x.5 20mm button or cap head machine screws
-Heavy duty adhesive velcro(optional)

You can get this all from Homedepot, Lowes, Runnings, Etc

Printer:

Baderbot 1500

Resolution:

.3mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Printed out of black PLA from Hatchbox.

Step 1

To help the screws fit better I drilled the holes out with a 1/8 inch drill bit. I also used some tweezers to remove any extra plastic in the nut holders.

Step 2

Unscrew the 4 bolts that are visible from the outside that hold the quads arms on. take the nuts and press them into the bottom of the mount.

Step 3

Attach velcro straps of your choosing thru the slots. I also added an extra piece of velcro to the bottom and to all by batteries. I would recommend this so your batteries don't fly out.

Step 4

Insert longer M3 bolts into the quad then into the mount. They might need a little convincing with a hammer or pliers. Then tighten the bolts up and your done
Dial calipers and Inventor.

title: Taranis Q X7, Q X7S Gimbal Protectors/Guards

description.text:
The Taranis Q X7 requires a smaller diameter gimbal guard than it's popular partner, the X9D. Unlike some other gimbal guards, these are not designed to be a substitute for a transmitter case as that would still leave your switches unprotected. Instead, they:
-Protect gimbals from crushing within the transmitter case
-Keep your transmitter case and foam in good condition by preventing sharp sticks from rubbing
-Preserve gimbal springs by maintaining a neutral stick position during transport

V2 is ideal for a Taranis with stock gimbals while V1 fits both stock and upgraded M7 hall gimbals.

If you're looking for an easy remix, simply make a copy of my public Onshape document.

If you don't own a 3D printer, I also have listed these on eBay.

Update: Added custom M7 hall gimbal protectors optimized to fit upgraded M7 hall gimbals and the Q X7S transmitter.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Use your defaults

10-100%

Notes:

V1 doesn't require supports, but V2 and M7 hall gimbal protectors do. For easy removal of support, set the support to model spacing to .4mm.

the (I hope for) more crash-proof version of pagoda (see here http://www.maartenbaert.be/quadcopters/antennas/pagoda-antenna/) 5.8GHz FPV antenna. Since I tend to crash hard too much I decided to devise more robust version than this https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2134929 (and I just did not much like the design of this one https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2278861). Also, my antenna had different (wrong) distance between bottom disks (10.2 vs 10.45) so I had to account for that.

Assembling: just put all parts in place and use two rings of thermo-shrinking tube to glue the pieces together. I've printed with modified PET which is believed to be more shock-proof than PLA or ABS, but you are welcome to use either

description.text:
External adjustement for the wasteboard of the R-CNC.
You need bolt and screw M5x25 (I used 14).

Make some slots in the aluminium corners (see picture).

Try to adjust a little the aluminium corners before putting the waste board.

Unscrew every screw a bit.

Take a piece of wood or aluminium as a reference.
Start at a corner, put the reference under the spindle, use clamps to pull the board against the spindle and screw (I used my shoulder to push against the X axis when pulling the board).
Make a whole side, then the opposite side, and then last sides.

Centrifugal fidget spinner

designed for 608 standard ball-bearing and 9mm ball-bearing-balls.

9mm balls are free to move in the arms of the spinner;
when rotating, they are pressed outside. Once it slows down, when spinning vertically, they drop down again and make nice, clickery sounds.
Spinning horizontally is silent - depending only on the bearing you use in the middle.

Assembly: fill one to three balls in each arm and push bearing in the middle. It's an easy fit, due to the open arms. Once I had my bearing fine, I secured it with a drop of super glue.

Original CAD data can be found and reused in Onshape:

Tap for 608 - bearing "608 tap":
https://cad.onshape.com/document-redirect.html?d=/documents/e26c115415e3a61a40bfa7b1/w/01e075720ce131a2232920a2

Fidget Spinner itself "centrifugal spinner":
https://cad.onshape.com/document-redirect.html?d=/documents/cd5d6b5ee77e86217893983a/w/087f49fa1bbc9eb1fda428d9

Yes

I printed 0,15 layer hights, 25% infill.

title: Audi V8 FSI Front Main Seal Install Tool

description.text:
Drew this to press the front main seal into an 09 A8 V8.
Prob works on quite a few motors from this era.

Use the cup that comes with the seal to guide the inner lip onto the crank.
Remove the cup without disturbing the seal.
Use this stl to push the seal on the rest of the way with the crank pulley bolts.
Might help to grab some bolts that are the same size as the crank bolts, but shorter.

Makes it so you wont have to yank the whole lock carrier to drive the seal in, or buy the expensive VAG tool.

title: Trash can
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I wanted a small trash can to sit beside my printer. It is amazing to me how many small bits of plastic I generate working this thing. Running to the store would have been a hell of a lot easier but where is the fun in that.
I printed a baby one first that would make a good pen cup to test my settings before printing out the big one.

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select v2.1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.32

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I don't plan to be too rough with the can so I opted for speed over strength with only .4 thick walls and 20% infill. Time will tell if that's too weak, but feels pretty good. A bit of flex to it and light weight but tougher than I thought it would be. The small pen cup is a good warm up to test. I kind of like how the infill overlap shows up on the outside.

Since my nozzle is .4 I did 80% of that for the height or .32. I read somewhere you should probably use a bit less on tall objects, but it came out great.

description.text: test it
try it

Hey guys and gals , whipped up this bracket for the Creality CR-10 that clips onto your extruder to give you an honest bed reading which makes corner to corner set up nice and easy as you can adjust the height and watch your levels in real time

I used simple earth magnets on the bottom for the mounting as they are WAY strong enough to clip to the top of the extruder

Note : when taking readings , go into your menu to and select the option that you can move your axis off the controller so that you dont push the head and force the meter into false readings

Link for the Vernier guage is : http://www.ebay.com.au/itm/LCD-Electronic-Digital-Gauge-Stainless-Vernier-Caliper-150mm-6inch-Micrometer-DD-/332227287245?var=&hash=item4d5a4a18cd:m:muUNIIV3xwFTyVxVWbtpsFw

I have no idea who this seller is but just giving you an example of the guage i used so check it out and if you can find 1 local then go for it ( you can keep the ruler full length of grind half off as i have done

title: Robo3d Titan Areo Upgrade Prusa Style

description.text:
THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS - I have yet to print these out and test them. I recently put an aluminum bed on and my stepper took a crap. I'm putting this out there if you want to experiment to try it out. I will update when I finally get up and running again.

. My goal with this was to maximize useable Z height while not sacrificing any X or Y print area. I also wanted to have a clean design that fully utilized the Areo fan setup. In order to do this, I felt I needed to change to a Prusa style X axis. I also tried to incorporate some of the popular upgrades into the design. So, here is a rundown of the design:
Prusa style X axis Redesign:
For this I took from this , https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2022223/#files, and I combined it with the counter weight upgrade, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2213625. When putting this together I recommend bolting up the motor to the right side part and weighing it with a kitchen scale and then add pennies to the left side until they both weigh the same and then use CA glue to lock the pennies in place.
Carriage:
With the carriage, there are a lot of considerations to take into account. Maximizing useable Z height while minimizing X and Y losses, Parts cooling, belt tension, wire organization, aesthetics and so on. The
Wire Organization:
First thing is I made it receive the same chain link wire loom that is used in this chassis, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1557214/#files, it’s the same chain chassis and chain link I was using before. Also in the realm of wire organization, I placed a couple of hole in the side of the chassis that you can run a zip tie through so you can neatly organize the wires from the extruder fan, heater and thermistor.
Parts Cooling:
I ended up incorporating the parts cooling fan into the chassis in an attempt to make everything fit in a nice clean package. Here is a cross section view.
Belt Tensioner:
I wanted to incorporate a couple of options for belt tension. Many people like the zip tie method which compatible with this but you can also use the designed belt tensioner which uses two bolts to tighten.
When printing the chassis, I recommend printing it on its side and placing your own supports as trying to take out the supports where the parts cooling fan duct is would be difficult. I also have a chassis for regular bearings and the quiet bushings. I also provide a file for an X axis leveling tool. I print 2 out and snap them on the X axis rods on opposite ends and do a quick paper level.
Well there it is I hope you like it.

  • Don't forget to take in to account thermal expansion and contraction when printing. if printing with a material that has a large amount of thermal expansion/contraction like ABS you may need to scale up the print accordingly.

title: RC Speed Tank Mod for small printers and Traxxas Hardware

description.text:
This is a mod of the amazing RC speed tank. My modifications are to allow the tank to be printed on a small printer. I broke up the big parts into pieces. I also wanted to use more commonly available gears and electronics so I modified the tank to use Traxxas spur gears instead of the printed gear in the original design. My tank has a Stampede spur gear and pinion. The spur is held to the printed wheel with steel screws. I also made the tensioning wheel a little bigger to tighten up the belt. This is a work in progress and some parts are missing. They have been lost from my design files so I will have to regenerate them. IF there is a lot of interest i will put more work in. Just message me. Needless to say the RC tank is for advanced builders. I've been 3D printing for 4 years and I struggled with it. Its well worth it as it is a great design and runs well.

Update: I think all the parts are uploaded now.

Might make an inverted version (with thin stabilizers to connect the bat to the circle) for other uses but it's not a high priority - feel free to remix. A screw controled tightening system for the Tronxy X1's sometimes wobbly y-bed.

Part C and D are optional and made to fit the spare M5 screw i had leftover. Required is a M5 Nut + a M5 screw with 25mm length (without part C+D) or 30mm length (with part C+D)

description.text: infin by ana [created on 3DTin]

openSCAD database of all convex polyhedra with regular faces except for prisms and anti-prisms. This includes the Platonic, Archimedean, and Johnson polyhedra (over 100 total!). Pictured are all the Platonic solids and a few Archimedean solids created with the customizer. I've also included platonic.stl for printing the 5 platonic solids, each scaled to be ~2 cm tall. This was built on some previous work: George Hart's VRML polyhedra models, (http://www.georgehart.com/virtual-polyhedra/vp.html) And pmoews' polyhedra Thingiverse designs (e.g. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16508), which have the face data from the VRML files converted to triangles to work with openSCAD.

In the customizer, there are 2 styles and 110 polyhedra to choose from. You can also adjust the thickness of the shell (default 30%). In your software, orient the polyhedron so the largest face lays flat on the print bed. platonic.stl has the 5 platonic solids (each created with the customizer) and will print in under 2 hours. Some minor issues with the "cutout" style:

  • The cutouts for the faces are with respect to the origin, not the normal of the face, so some Johnson polyhedra which have faces with normals that do not intersect the origin will not have perfectly centered cutouts.

  • Face normals are not pre-computed, so rendering can be slow for large objects.

remixed_from.title: Anet A2 X Axis belt tensioner

title: X Axis Belt Tensioner for Anet A2 Tevo Tarantula, simplified + strengthened

description.text:
I took the belt holder and improved it so that it would work for first time prints. This is just the belt holder, not the whole assembly, get the whole assembly from these things:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1748326
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2201478

I broke 5 of the original belt holders, so I simplified and strengthened it to work for a first time print.

The problem with the original belt holders is that they use the hexagon shape that the nut is supposed to rest in, but if you don't have a tight x and y axis (which you wont yet if you're printing this part) you can't accurately print that hex shape. So the nut ends up sitting on top of it's recess instead of in it, which only gives you a couple mm of clearence to screw into the bolt. Also, the original didn't have a very thick radius on the rod part which means it can snap very easily as you tighten the x-axis.

This file is a much thicker part and simpler to print for a first time print.

description.text: I love my BIBO and if you're like me and you like to experiment then you've probably had your BIBO in pieces many times cleaning up messes and straightening things out. The wire fan covers were kind of a pain if you have to keep putting the fans on and off, especially if you want to leave the thing running. print_settings.Notes:: In attempt to minimize supports, I added removable material at the recessed screw mounts, and the duct only needs a small handful of 1mm supports at the transition point just in front of the blower opening.  The rings doesn't need any support.

description.text:
There are a number of different Monoprice Ultimate / Wanhao D6 fan duct replacements out there, but they seem complicated, large, and encumbered the heat sink cooling. This design takes the lightweight design from JGTMaker and makes it blower compatible. Many of the blowers either didn't use all 3 of the original mounting screws, or added structure for custom mounts to keep the ducts from sagging. I tried to keep this as simple, compact, and light as possible.

I have not run any tests yet, and if any of you have, please share the results.

Update 5/29/2017:
I've runs prints (not tests) with 60d overhang and was successful when I wasn't before, so it is doing what I need it to do.

Added a new version for you folks having sagging issues with JGTMaker's original version using the stock fan, the blower modification inherently has more support, but I added a 2nd version with additional support for the cantilevered part of the ring. Until I have sagging issues, I will not print and mount it, but if you folks print it post you've made it, and let us know how it is working for you.

Update 6/26/2017

Modified V3 with additional support to V4 to redirect the airflow down a little. One user said the blower might be cooling the extruder tip too much and was causing errors. Haven't tested it, but I hope it works.

Update 7/23/2017

V6 has additional openings to redirect the airflow down more, and reduce the air hitting the extruder tip. Haven't printed or tested it, but I hope it works.

comments.text: I considered this, and modeled it up, but I ran into a number of problems.  The blower height and material support drives that dimension, so there was no gain in distance from the bed, plus if you raise it too much it affects the cooling, plus it could cool the nozzle even more (already an issue).  The blower intake is on top, but it could be flipped but would create more mass extending out in front of the nozzle, and would block the viewing cutout.  Also if it is flipped it could draw material into the blower if a print failure occurred.

blog post

CryptoPlastic

What do you get when you cross Bitcoin with 3D printing?

A Bitcoin Paper wallet

Except it's plastic. They say you don't own the coin unless you own the private key.
Safer than paper, more insecure than steel.

This can be used to store your private key. Make sure you print enough letters. This wallet
can hold a maximum of 16 characters per line. 64 characters total. This means you can store:

  • Private Key WIF (51 characters base58, starts with a '5')
  • Private Key Hexadecimal Format (64 characters [0-9A-F])
  • Private Key BIP38 Format (58 characters base58, starts with '6P')

You can view it in 3D here.

To test it out, I will hodl some Bitcoin here: 1FVjCBrdA2rKZKq6jyAZQQ12erZxHk9UXd. Feel free to donate :)

For the paranoid

This 3D print also includes a 1d16 hex die. By rolling it 64 times and writing down the
values, you are in fact generating a bitcoin private key (in hexadecimal format).

Test prints

I am currently printing this on Yellow PLA with a layer height of 200.

The final print is 18cm x 10.4cm x 1.13cm. Once the print arrives, I will post
photos.

Important

  • If you lose coins because of this wallet, it is your fault, it provides
    no guarantees
  • This is an alternative to CryptoSteel
  • I DO NOT recommend this over CryptoSteel

EDIT 3: I have added left and right split file for those of you that use routers (?).
EDIT 2: Ive widened (?) the slot/channel thingy for the buffer tube and fixed the beaver tail and applied these changes to the half-models.
EDIT: I've added files for the stock in 2 parts for those of you that have smaller printers. there are two registers between the parts for alignment and joint strength.

This is the Hera CQR stock for M-4/AR-15 pattern AEG airsoft rifles. The design is not 100% the same as the real-steel version as the pistol grip has to house the motor. The measurements for the interface are from the lancer tactical LT-12, this may not fit your gun exactly, however, it should fit most.

Butt-pads with different textures and desgins are coming soon!
Matching foregrip!
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2331717

ASSEMBLY:
-Remove the stock, motor, and pistol grip from your current gun. Set aside the screws used to secure the pistol grip to the gearbox, as well as the endcap/radiator for the motor, these will be used later.
-Slide the stock onto your gun's buffer tube, before it is slid completely on, route the motor wires through the holes in the grip-section.
-Once the stock is slid all the way down, use the screw you set aside earlier to affix the grip to the gearbox.
-Next insert the Body retaining pin (or a similarly-sized pin) into the hole near the base of the buffer tube.
-Insert the motor into the motor housing, attach the motor wires, and secure th motor in the housing with the endcap/radiator from the old pistol grip by screwing it into the holes at the bottom of the grip.
-Next slide the motor plate into the channel so that it looks like the pictures above.
-Slide the butt pad into it's registers in the back of the stock.
-Finally, insert 1/8 inch (3.175 mm) pins in to the holes marked with red circles.

comments.text: Does this case allow you to use plate-mount switches, or are pcb-mount switches still preferable?
comments.author: Tinfoil_Haberdashery

comments.text: In my experience that depends on the PCB. I've used cherry and gaterons switches. The only difference between plate and pcb mount switches are that pcb mount switches have an extra two plastic prongs that fit into the pcb. Where the two different types of switches mate to the plate is exactly the same. I prefer PCB mount switches since they align better but of course if your pcb doesn't have the holes for the prongs, they won't fit. But you could easily just snap the prongs off to make them fit in this case. Hope that helps!
comments.author: Tinfoil_Haberdashery

comments.text: So I understand, but it's my impression that plate mount type switches, lacking the stabilizers through the pcb, benefit from extra support provided by the case; I was wondering if this case provides that.
comments.author: mesohuannny

comments.text: No there's nothing additional in this print that would provide stabilization, the switches fit snug into the plate but I wouldn't say that it is as secure as a metal plate. The soldering to the PCB helps keep everything secured and supported but that said, I always prefer PCB mounted switches still. Those extra prongs help keep everything perfectly aligned.

title: Hayward ColorLogic Face Rim and Mount

description.text:
Adding to my ever-growing list of obscure replacement parts, I present to you the Hayward ColorLogic Face Rim and Mounting plastics. I'm sorry, I don't know the exact model number this is for... but I'm trying to find out.

These are the plastic parts for a colored light system that goes in pools and spas. Apparently, you just can't get these by themselves, you must buy an entire new light assembly, so a customer of mine asked me if I could reproduce one. It took a fair bit of CAD work, but I pulled it off.

I'm listing this as non-commercial, but if someone out there wants to make these and sell them, I think there is a market and I'm willing to talk about royalties. Otherwise, if it is just for yourself or a friend, have at it. A lot of work went into this, so I would feel better if other people could use it, otherwise it seems a waste.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker Original

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

lots

Notes:

These printed out nicely at 0.2mm layer height. I tried to use ABS, but the warp factor got the better of me so I ended up going with PETG. Time will tell if it holds up to the pool chemicals. The original parts were polypropylene, which I've heard is even worse than ABS to print with. At any rate, I'd go heavy on the infill. You want these to be pretty much solid.

The "Rim" will have to be printed with support, and it sucks to remove it. I'm sorry about that. The "Mount" was sliced in half to avoid the need for support, but you will have to glue the two halves together after printing.

After you print the parts, you will have to painstakingly remove the support material from the rim. You will also have to glue the two halves of the mount together. After all that, you will probably have to drill out the holes as needed to accommodate your screws.
This was reverse-engineered from original parts, and knocked up in a CAD program called Fusion 360.
